Perfect, this is essentially a Linux system administration exercise involving user/group management, directory setup, permissions, and access control. Let me walk you through the exact commands step by step so you can replicate this on a Linux system.
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ Step 1: Create Users and Groups
# Create users
sudo useradd alice
sudo useradd bob
sudo useradd carol

# Create group devteam
sudo groupadd devteam

# Add bob and carol to devteam
sudo usermod -aG devteam bob
sudo usermod -aG devteam carol
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ Step 2: Setup Project Directory
# Create /project directory
sudo mkdir /project

# Assign ownership
sudo chown alice:devteam /project

# Set permissions: owner + group full access, others none
sudo chmod 770 /project
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ Step 3: Create Files with Specific Permissions
a) Project Plan File
# Switch to alice
sudo -u alice touch /project/project_plan.txt

# Permissions: alice can read/write, others can only read
sudo chmod 644 /project/project_plan.txt
b) Source Code Directory
# Create src directory owned by bob with group devteam
sudo mkdir /project/src
sudo chown bob:devteam /project/src

# Permissions: bob + devteam full access, others none
sudo chmod 770 /project/src
c) Script File build.sh
# Create build.sh as bob
sudo -u bob touch /project/src/build.sh

# Make it executable, but only bob can execute
sudo chmod 744 /project/src/build.sh
â€¢	7 â†’ bob: read/write/execute
â€¢	4 â†’ group: read only
â€¢	4 â†’ others: read only
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ Step 4: Set Default Permissions for New Files in /project/src
a) Ensure group inheritance
# Set SGID bit so new files inherit devteam group
sudo chmod g+s /project/src
b) Configure default umask
To enforce owner RW and group R only:
# Create ACL default rule
sudo setfacl -d -m u::rw /project/src
sudo setfacl -d -m g::r /project/src
sudo setfacl -d -m o::0 /project/src
________________________________________
ðŸ”¹ Step 5: User Access Tests
a) Carol edits project_plan.txt (should fail)
sudo -u carol nano /project/project_plan.txt
# â†’ Permission denied for writing
b) Bob executes build.sh (should succeed)
sudo -u bob /project/src/build.sh
# â†’ Executes successfully
c) Carol executes build.sh (should fail)
sudo -u carol /project/src/build.sh
# â†’ Permission denied (no execute permission)
d) Alice views contents of /project/src
sudo -u alice ls -l /project/src
Expected output:
-rwxr--r-- 1 bob devteam 0 Jan  8 22:20 build.sh
